					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-7440419#post-3965146</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-7440419/scp-4414#post-3965146</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Tue, 11 Sep 2018 06:40:20 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>Zzuxon</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>1496981</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>I like this a lot. The image is creepy and sets tone well. The build-up in the description from what the picture does to what it depicts is great, with the &quot;payoff&quot; (Picking at skin tags) being something that is strange enough to be interesting but familiar enough to be relatable. And those interviews, especially the last one, are a great end.</p> <p>The idea of people wanting to remove their skin in one long, thin strip coiling around their body so that they don't have to deal with skin tags is inspired creep and creates great imagery.</p> <p>Main criticisms:<br /> The title should be SCP-4414, not &quot;Scp 4414.&quot;</p> <p>I don't feel like the note at the top adds very much to the article. The only info it adds is that the image is spreading very quickly, which could easily be mentioned in the article proper. And somewhat clumsy lines like</p> <blockquote> <p>And if you ever see what this thing makes people do, you'll understand why — at least for a few moments.</p> </blockquote> <p>Do a poor job of setting tone, especially in comparison to the image. I honestly think the article would be improved if the entire thing was removed.</p> <blockquote> <p>They often attempt self-termination or terminate through anomalous — while naturally plausible — means.</p> </blockquote> <p>This line doesn't make any sense until the interview logs show someone having a seizure for no reason. The sentence should be reworked.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
